WEBVTT

01:25.335 --> 01:28.588
Since I got here,
you're my third contempt of court.

01:28.672 --> 01:30.631
First one was a contested traffic ticket.

01:30.716 --> 01:31.716
The guy cursed at the judge.

01:31.800 --> 01:33.426
The second one was a lawyer.

01:33.510 --> 01:35.803
-What'd he do?
-He cursed at the judge.

01:35.888 --> 01:38.264
--You're my first reporter.

01:38.348 --> 01:40.641
-I'm Will. I'd shake your hand...
-I know who you are.

01:42.352 --> 01:44.687
So the traffic ticket,
he was just here for a night.

01:44.772 --> 01:46.564
But the lawyer was here for a weekend.

01:46.648 --> 01:49.484
Three nights, and you could tell
he was starting to go a little...

01:49.568 --> 01:52.987
You know, it affected him.

01:55.157 --> 01:58.743
You're gonna be locked in a cage now,
and it's not a natural thing.

01:58.827 --> 02:00.495
Go ahead.

02:00.954 --> 02:02.705
That's yours over here.

02:04.708 --> 02:06.793
-You got toiletries?
-I'm sorry?

02:06.877 --> 02:08.377
You didn't bring toiletries?

02:08.462 --> 02:10.463
Uh, no, I didn't.

02:10.714 --> 02:12.340
I'll bring you toothpaste and a brush.

02:12.424 --> 02:14.509
I can bring you a book from the library
if you want.

02:14.593 --> 02:17.261
-You might get the whole weekend.
-Sure, thanks.

02:17.638 --> 02:19.597
You'll be fine.

02:36.573 --> 02:38.282
You fish.

02:38.826 --> 02:40.243
I'm sorry?

02:40.911 --> 02:42.662
You're a fisherman.

02:44.540 --> 02:46.874
Yeah. No. Not in a long time.

02:48.335 --> 02:49.794
That's a nice fish.

02:49.878 --> 02:51.838
-Yeah.
-Eight pounds.

02:51.922 --> 02:53.881
You know, I don't really remember.

02:53.966 --> 02:55.508
And that's your father there next to you?

02:56.009 --> 02:58.594
-Yeah.
-That's a wholesome picture.

02:58.679 --> 03:00.346
Looks like it came with the frame.

03:00.430 --> 03:02.682
-Yeah.
-And that's your wife?

03:02.766 --> 03:04.433
Yeah, her name is MacKenzie.

03:04.518 --> 03:06.853
-Whew, she's a knockout.
-She is.

03:06.937 --> 03:10.189
-It's okay if I say that, right?
-Sure.

03:10.274 --> 03:13.276
And those are your, what?
Your friends, your colleagues?

03:13.944 --> 03:17.280
Yeah, they're some of the people I work with.

03:17.364 --> 03:19.115
We work close together.

03:19.700 --> 03:22.243
-You have to explain it to me one more time.
-Really?

03:22.327 --> 03:24.996
'Cause every time you say it,
it sounds like you're in here voluntarily.

03:25.122 --> 03:26.497
I promise you, I'm not.

03:26.582 --> 03:28.499
But you can walk out any time you want.

03:28.584 --> 03:32.962
No, I can't. I can only walk out
if I reveal the identity of a source.

03:33.338 --> 03:36.007
-You want to read your book.
-I don't want to be rude.

03:38.218 --> 03:40.887
You didn't ask me what I was in for.
I appreciate that.

03:43.724 --> 03:45.600
Domestic battery.

03:45.684 --> 03:47.393
Nine women on the jury.

03:48.687 --> 03:52.231
My PD was a woman,
so she wasn't exactly my champion.

03:52.316 --> 03:54.191
The prosecutor was a woman.

03:54.276 --> 03:55.985
The judge was a woman.

03:56.069 --> 03:57.904
I mean,
is that even constitutional?

03:57.988 --> 04:00.406
The PD wanted me to plea six months.

04:00.490 --> 04:03.034
But I wanted to fight it. Two years.

04:03.118 --> 04:05.828
That wasn't your first offense, though.

04:06.455 --> 04:07.580
How do you know?

04:07.664 --> 04:11.000
You wouldn't have gotten two years
for domestic battery if it was your first...

04:11.084 --> 04:13.002
It was my third. Strike three.

04:14.254 --> 04:16.255
Oh, are you judging me now?

04:16.340 --> 04:18.090
'Cause a judge just did that. I don't need it.

04:18.175 --> 04:20.009
-No.
-Yeah, you are.

04:21.053 --> 04:22.637
I have an idea.

04:22.721 --> 04:24.430
Tell me the name of the source.

04:24.556 --> 04:26.474
I didn't make a pledge or anything.

04:26.558 --> 04:29.644
I'll tell it to them
on the condition they let us both go.

04:29.811 --> 04:31.103
It's a hell of a plan.

04:31.188 --> 04:33.356
Or I could just shake the name out of you.

04:34.483 --> 04:35.483
Stand up.

04:38.737 --> 04:42.156
I want you to see that I got four inches on you
and you're giving up 30 pounds.

04:42.240 --> 04:43.783
I'm not your wife.

04:43.867 --> 04:47.703
Raise your hands above your hips
and I'll knock you the fuck into next week.

04:56.838 --> 04:58.673
Your father was a drunk, wasn't he?

05:02.260 --> 05:05.012
You aren't a consumer,
<i>you're a citizen.</i>

05:05.097 --> 05:07.640
<i>You aren't an audience, you're an activist.</i>

05:07.724 --> 05:10.142
<i>You aren't a viewer, you're ACN.</i>

05:10.227 --> 05:12.770
<i>You are ACN.</i>

05:21.947 --> 05:23.072
Which one of you...

05:23.156 --> 05:25.825
It's exactly as offensive as I thought
it was gonna be when I heard about it.

05:25.909 --> 05:28.035
-Offensive to whom?
-Me. And him.

05:28.120 --> 05:31.288
And Will and Sloan
and everyone who works here, and you.

05:31.373 --> 05:34.083
-We are ACN.
-It's a slogan. It doesn't mean anything.

05:34.167 --> 05:36.669
First, I wouldn't be relieved
that our new slogan doesn't mean anything.

05:36.753 --> 05:38.254
-I meant...
-But it isn't a slogan.

05:38.338 --> 05:40.381
It's a statement of our new direction.

05:40.465 --> 05:43.759
We're gonna cover the conversation
because this is just the first one.

05:43.844 --> 05:47.847
Next one's gonna show citizen journalists
filing stories from the Coffee Bean.

05:47.931 --> 05:50.016
-Don?
-It looks like urine.

05:50.100 --> 05:51.100
- It doesn't.

05:51.184 --> 05:52.476
You're just complaining for the sake of it.

05:52.561 --> 05:57.440
The best graphics house in the UK
was paid $700,000 to build that spot.

05:57.524 --> 06:00.317
I don't mean the animation. U-r-a-c-n.

06:00.402 --> 06:02.361
Our brains are trained
to see groups of letters as a word

06:02.446 --> 06:04.864
and visually,
that group of letters looks like urine.

06:05.657 --> 06:08.325
Maybe if we separate the U and the R.

06:08.410 --> 06:09.535
Maybe, but the best you can hope for

06:09.619 --> 06:11.746
is something with the gravitas
of a vanity license plate.

06:11.830 --> 06:14.540
Maybe we should
ask people to vote. After all, they are ACN.

06:14.624 --> 06:15.583
You know, Mac...

06:15.667 --> 06:17.460
Young people know
when they're being patronized.

06:17.544 --> 06:19.045
Everybody knows
when they're being patronized.

06:19.129 --> 06:21.047
I've been hearing this for 52 days.

06:21.131 --> 06:23.382
Because in 52 days,

06:23.467 --> 06:26.135
I've put three Twitter monitors on our set.

06:26.219 --> 06:29.513
Passing weather systems
are reported like al-Qaeda sleeper cells.

06:29.598 --> 06:33.392
And a total of 84 air minutes
have been spent on the mayor of Toronto

06:33.477 --> 06:35.728
while zero minutes
have been spent on the mayor of Detroit

06:35.812 --> 06:39.065
whose city is about
two minutes away from bankruptcy.

06:39.149 --> 06:41.400
Also in that 52 days, we've gone from fourth

06:41.485 --> 06:43.360
to third in households
and second in the demo.

06:43.445 --> 06:44.737
--In seven weeks,

06:44.821 --> 06:48.407
the average age of our audience
has dropped three years.

06:48.492 --> 06:53.996
And we did all that while still managing
to cover a military takeover in Egypt

06:54.081 --> 06:58.417
and most recently,
a pretty big scandal involving the NSA.

06:58.502 --> 07:01.504
We've got two reporters
at the Moscow Airport right now.

07:01.671 --> 07:05.132
Two. So can you do me a favor and not worry

07:05.217 --> 07:09.845
that the world's most benign promo
is a threat to democracy?

07:09.930 --> 07:11.555
-Sure.
-You?

07:11.640 --> 07:13.599
-Can I have a second?
-Yeah.

07:16.436 --> 07:18.229
So, the Princeton story. The website.

07:18.855 --> 07:22.858
There is an epidemic
of campus sexual assault in this country.

07:22.943 --> 07:24.819
It's a perfectly legitimate story.

07:24.903 --> 07:27.988
In fact, it's an important one,
so what's your fucking problem?

07:28.073 --> 07:29.615
I agree.

07:29.699 --> 07:32.284
-I just don't know how to do the story.
-I don't understand.

07:32.369 --> 07:34.245
I don't know how to do it.
I'm looking for some guidance.

07:34.329 --> 07:36.163
You interview the student with the website.

07:36.248 --> 07:38.207
You interview
one of the guys who's been accused.

07:38.291 --> 07:39.458
Why is it complicated?

07:39.543 --> 07:41.585
Well, it's complicated for a lot of reasons,

07:41.670 --> 07:44.213
and one of them is that
Pruit wants them both in the studio.

07:44.297 --> 07:46.465
-He told you that?
-He called me.

07:51.596 --> 07:54.098
He shouldn't be speaking directly to you.

07:54.182 --> 07:56.308
And he shouldn't be making those decisions.

07:56.393 --> 07:57.560
But if that's what he wants,

07:57.644 --> 07:59.562
- why don't you just do it?

08:04.317 --> 08:06.152
Well, like I said, I don't know how to.

08:06.236 --> 08:07.486
Bullshit.

08:07.737 --> 08:09.405
You do know how.

08:10.240 --> 08:14.076
And if you don't,
I need to hire someone who does, man.

08:14.619 --> 08:15.828
Okay?

08:17.205 --> 08:18.330
Yeah.

08:19.749 --> 08:21.083
Anything else?

08:21.376 --> 08:22.877
No.

08:34.639 --> 08:37.558
Anything happen over the weekend
I should know about?

08:37.642 --> 08:39.351
Not much.

08:39.436 --> 08:42.021
Dilma Rousseff pledged
to speak with protestors.

08:42.105 --> 08:44.064
-The House voted down the Farm Bill.
-Yeah, I saw that.

08:44.149 --> 08:47.484
France is sending Syrian rebels
17.6 tons of medical aid.

08:47.569 --> 08:49.695
I'm sure that's going to get
where it's supposed to go.

08:49.779 --> 08:51.780
A woman named
Lilly M. Hart shot herself in the mouth

08:51.865 --> 08:53.824
on the steps in front
of the Justice Department.

08:53.909 --> 08:55.326
We're not sure what she was protesting,

08:55.410 --> 08:58.078
but her bio had
a lot of gun control advocacy in it.

08:58.163 --> 09:00.497
She was protesting guns by shooting herself?

09:00.582 --> 09:02.750
The FBI isn't releasing
any information right now.

09:02.834 --> 09:05.127
-You mean DC Police.
-No, the FBI is handling it.

09:05.212 --> 09:08.214
-Why?
-They won't release that information either.

09:08.298 --> 09:09.465
Anything else?

09:09.549 --> 09:11.383
Kim and Kanye named their baby North.

09:11.468 --> 09:13.427
There's our top story.

09:14.679 --> 09:16.263
What was her name?

09:16.473 --> 09:18.265
North. North West.

09:18.350 --> 09:20.976
No, the woman
who shot herself in front of the DOJ.

09:21.269 --> 09:22.728
Lilly Hart.

09:23.521 --> 09:25.397
Again, I don't know how...

09:27.067 --> 09:28.234
What?

09:31.488 --> 09:33.280
She wasn't protesting guns.

09:35.575 --> 09:38.202
They said it was an emergency.
Is everything okay?

09:38.286 --> 09:40.246
Do we have attorney-client privilege,
you and me?

09:40.330 --> 09:42.248
-I'm not your lawyer.
-What if you were?

09:42.332 --> 09:44.083
Then we would have that privilege.

09:44.167 --> 09:48.754
I'm hiring you right now on a $20 retainer.

09:48.838 --> 09:50.798
-Do I need to sign something?
-No. What's going on?

09:50.882 --> 09:52.925
I know the name of the source.

09:53.009 --> 09:55.469
I've known since the party
after the Correspondents' Dinner.

09:55.553 --> 09:57.596
And the day before yesterday,
she shot and killed herself

09:57.681 --> 09:59.556
on the steps outside the DOJ.

09:59.641 --> 10:02.518
-The woman... She was the source?
-Yeah.

10:03.520 --> 10:05.062
Who else knows the name?

10:05.146 --> 10:07.022
Neal, obviously, Will, and I. That's it.

10:07.107 --> 10:09.608
-Not the DC Police?
-I think they must...

10:09.985 --> 10:11.151
Excuse me.

10:12.529 --> 10:14.321
Thank you.

10:14.406 --> 10:16.365
Lasenthal on the phone.

10:18.994 --> 10:20.452
You know what?

10:20.954 --> 10:23.122
Your husband is getting out of jail today.

10:34.509 --> 10:36.802
I was just chewed out for
10 minutes by Erin Andrews.

10:36.886 --> 10:38.929
-Why?
-She was accosted by paparazzi last night

10:39.014 --> 10:40.889
coming out of Man of Steel
at the El Capitan in LA.

10:41.057 --> 10:42.474
Paparazzi were coming out of the El Capitan?

10:42.559 --> 10:43.726
-She...
-She was coming.

10:43.810 --> 10:46.145
She'd just seen the movie
and waiting for her were a pack of paparazzi.

10:46.229 --> 10:47.313
Got it. Why was she chewing you out?

10:47.397 --> 10:48.480
I'm the one here she knows the best.

10:48.565 --> 10:49.565
Didn't she have an affair with Will?

10:49.649 --> 10:51.650
It wasn't an affair.
Neither of them were married.

10:51.735 --> 10:54.820
No, that didn't happen. Will's in jail
at the moment. And none of this is the point.

10:54.904 --> 10:57.906
The paparazzi knew she was in there
because of our creepy stalker app.

10:57.991 --> 10:59.658
I'm coming to you as my superior,

10:59.743 --> 11:02.328
which I mean only in a sense of
our organizational chart,

11:02.412 --> 11:03.996
and pleading with you
to have what's his name...

11:04.080 --> 11:05.956
-Bree.
-Bree shut down the app.

11:06.041 --> 11:07.791
Mac's been fighting that battle for six weeks.

11:07.876 --> 11:10.794
-And what have you been doing?
-Just, you know, my job.

11:10.879 --> 11:13.505
Which should now include
getting the assassin's helper taken down.

11:13.590 --> 11:14.840
-I'm on it.
-When?

11:14.924 --> 11:18.510
Well, I'm in the middle of a tricky... Now.

11:18.595 --> 11:20.637
-Right now.
-There you go.

11:24.476 --> 11:26.435
Excuse me, Bree.

11:28.188 --> 11:29.188
Excuse me.

11:32.984 --> 11:34.568
Hey, easy.

11:34.652 --> 11:36.612
-I just wanted to talk to you about something.
-You are?

11:36.696 --> 11:38.822
He's Don Keefer, executive producer...
You know who he is.

11:38.907 --> 11:40.657
And you run our website
until Neal Sampat's back.

11:40.742 --> 11:41.742
I wanted to...

11:41.826 --> 11:44.244
I'm senior editor of ACN Digital,
if you're going to be insulting.

11:44.329 --> 11:46.455
-Nobody wants to be insulting.
-I badly want to be insulting.

11:46.539 --> 11:48.248
Here's the thing.
Sloan got a call from Erin Andrews...

11:48.333 --> 11:49.458
- You know Erin Andrews?
- Yes.

11:49.542 --> 11:51.877
Yowza. I want to get with that so bad.

11:51.961 --> 11:54.713
I'll pass that on.
I'm sure she'll want you to have her number.

11:54.798 --> 11:56.715
-Hey, fuck you.
-Yeah?

11:56.800 --> 11:59.468
-Oh, you can't talk to her like that, my friend.
-What's the problem here?

11:59.552 --> 12:01.136
Erin Andrews got stalked
by paparazzi last night

12:01.221 --> 12:02.221
coming out of the movies.

12:02.305 --> 12:04.390
-I know, we've got it up.
-Now we're in Peabody country.

12:04.474 --> 12:06.183
You're here to give me shit
about the app again.

12:06.267 --> 12:08.852
Yes. Restraining Order. Scum Bottle Guide.

12:08.937 --> 12:10.646
-Whatever it's called.
-ACNgage.

12:10.730 --> 12:12.272
It should be called ACInvoluntary Engage.

12:12.357 --> 12:13.982
I'll bring that up at our next staff meeting.

12:14.067 --> 12:16.485
-You guys like ACInvoluntary Engage?
-No.

12:16.569 --> 12:17.903
It got voted down.

12:17.987 --> 12:21.156
Listen, no kidding around, you need
to disable the app until we can figure this out,

12:21.241 --> 12:22.783
'cause it's a little not what we do.

12:22.867 --> 12:24.201
What's not what you do?

12:24.285 --> 12:26.412
Giving deranged people
with access to semiautomatic weapons

12:26.496 --> 12:27.704
the locations of their targets,

12:27.789 --> 12:30.165
while simultaneously
turning the rest of our brains into Wheatena.

12:30.250 --> 12:31.708
That app's driving a lot of traffic.

12:31.793 --> 12:33.585
I don't care if it's driving
in the Grand Prix of Monaco.

12:33.670 --> 12:35.003
I need you to temporarily take it down.

12:35.088 --> 12:37.506
- Then permanently take it down.
- You need to speak to my boss.

12:37.590 --> 12:38.757
-He's your boss.
-I'm your boss.

12:38.842 --> 12:42.052
Lucas Pruit is my boss. I pitched him the app
and he loved it, which is why we have it.

12:42.137 --> 12:43.971
This is a warmed-over version
of the same app Gawker had

12:44.055 --> 12:45.639
and took down five years ago.

12:45.723 --> 12:47.641
They still have a version of it,
but this one's better.

12:47.725 --> 12:48.725
- Look...
- No, you look.

12:48.810 --> 12:52.229
We're all a little tired of being treated
like we're not Neal Sampat.

12:52.313 --> 12:54.440
I like my app and it makes money,

12:54.524 --> 12:56.275
both of which are more
than I can say for your 10:00 hour.

12:56.359 --> 12:58.652
So if you have a problem,
and I got a hunch you got more than a few,

12:58.736 --> 13:00.571
why don't you take it to Pruit?

13:02.490 --> 13:04.283
- Beat him up.

13:05.952 --> 13:08.245
No, he's right.

13:08.329 --> 13:09.955
Yeah, he's... What?

13:10.039 --> 13:12.916
About the last thing he said.
About the last thing you said.

13:13.001 --> 13:14.543
We haven't been very welcoming

13:14.627 --> 13:17.212
and in a weird way
we've been blaming him for Neal.

13:17.881 --> 13:21.091
If Digital can help us,
we should be supporting Digital.

13:21.384 --> 13:23.635
-That's right.
-Yeah.

13:23.720 --> 13:25.471
Come on the show
and tell people about your app.

13:27.557 --> 13:28.599
Seriously?

13:28.683 --> 13:31.268
I'll ask MacKenzie for a block
and I'll interview you.

13:31.352 --> 13:33.479
All right. Awesome.

13:33.563 --> 13:35.647
An associate producer
will give you the details.

13:35.732 --> 13:37.566
-You should apologize.
-Sorry.

13:37.650 --> 13:39.651
-To him.
-Habit. Sorry.

13:39.736 --> 13:41.153
Were you serious about that phone number?

13:41.237 --> 13:43.489
Yeah, but I think you can do better.

13:43.573 --> 13:45.365
-For real?
-I'm on it.

13:50.997 --> 13:52.706
Okay, so when you vivisect this guy

13:52.790 --> 13:55.083
and especially his app,
Pruit's not gonna be happy.

13:55.168 --> 13:56.668
I'll cross that bridge when I come to it.

13:56.753 --> 13:58.712
You usually blow up that bridge
when you come to it.

13:58.796 --> 14:01.131
Would you mind giving me some space?
I have a show to prepare.

14:01.216 --> 14:02.591
Sure, but this is my office.

14:02.675 --> 14:04.218
Yes, it is. Sorry.

14:04.302 --> 14:05.302
Hang on.

14:06.429 --> 14:08.597
There's an undergrad at Princeton
who started a website

14:08.681 --> 14:09.806
for students who have been raped,

14:09.891 --> 14:12.684
but who don't have enough evidence
for the police to take action.

14:12.936 --> 14:16.563
Victims can go onto the site
either anonymously or not

14:16.648 --> 14:20.108
and name names
and describe their experiences.

14:20.193 --> 14:24.571
Pruit wants the undergrad
and one of the accused in the studio.

14:24.656 --> 14:26.031
-That's a terrible idea.
-I know.

14:26.115 --> 14:27.491
-Do you have a better one?
-Don't do it?

14:27.575 --> 14:30.035
Do you have a better one
where I get to keep my job?

14:30.119 --> 14:31.203
Charlie's gonna back you.

14:31.287 --> 14:32.788
Charlie told me to do it.

14:35.792 --> 14:37.459
What's happening to him?

14:40.129 --> 14:42.548
I think you should consider
letting me do the talking.

14:42.632 --> 14:45.217
At least at the top.
We won't have much time with him

14:45.301 --> 14:48.929
and I want to ask him, obviously, the extent
to which they've been keeping metadata,

14:49.013 --> 14:51.223
how much the agency
learns from this kind of information,

14:51.307 --> 14:55.269
and in what ways the FISA reports have
provided insufficient oversight of the NSA.

14:55.353 --> 14:58.230
I want to ask him at what point he
decided to declare war on the United States.

14:58.314 --> 15:00.440
So I think you should
let me get the ball rolling.

15:00.525 --> 15:03.068
You and your whole generation's
contempt for institutions.

15:03.152 --> 15:04.111
I'm two years younger than you.

15:04.195 --> 15:05.904
With your hair,
and your clothes and your music.

15:05.989 --> 15:07.406
Here it is. Here's the gate.

15:07.490 --> 15:08.532
You sure?

15:08.616 --> 15:11.577
It says, departs for Havana at 11:55 p.m.

15:11.661 --> 15:14.746
-Are you sure?
-We had a nine-hour flight from New York.

15:14.831 --> 15:17.291
I was brushing up on my Russian
with my Russian phrase book,

15:17.375 --> 15:20.752
<i>or Russkiy razgovornik, while you</i>
were watching Star Wars on your iPad.

15:20.837 --> 15:22.546
<i>Trek. Star Trek.</i>

15:22.630 --> 15:25.007
Both excellent examples of genius,

15:25.091 --> 15:27.009
-but different in every imaginable...
-Yeah, shut up.

15:27.093 --> 15:28.719
-Good evening.
-Good evening.

15:34.517 --> 15:36.143
Then we'll speak in English.

15:36.227 --> 15:37.894
You're American press, yes?

15:37.979 --> 15:40.772
I have not seen Edward Snowden.
I do not know where he is.

15:40.857 --> 15:44.276
That's all right. We just wanna check in
for the midnight flight to Havana.

15:44.360 --> 15:46.486
That's Aeroflot seven, departing 11:55?

15:46.571 --> 15:49.114
Yes. Margaret Jordan and James Humdrum.

15:49.198 --> 15:50.198
Harper.

15:51.743 --> 15:54.494
That guy's from ABC's Moscow bureau.

15:55.705 --> 15:58.332
And that's Reuters and that's Le Monde.

15:58.416 --> 16:00.667
He's going to Cuba.
He's gonna be on this flight.

16:00.752 --> 16:02.961
I do not show
reservation for Margaret Jordan.

16:03.046 --> 16:04.838
-Really?
-I'll try Humdrum.

16:04.922 --> 16:06.340
Harper. James Harper.

16:06.424 --> 16:09.926
The office bought our tickets
while we were in the air.

16:10.011 --> 16:12.262
I do not show reservation for Harper.

16:12.347 --> 16:13.764
Would you mind checking again?

16:13.848 --> 16:15.432
What do you think will
happen the second time?

16:17.518 --> 16:20.020
Would you ask her to check again?

16:20.104 --> 16:22.606
-Would you mind checking again?
-In Russian.

16:22.690 --> 16:25.609
I understood in English.
And I have checked again.

16:25.693 --> 16:28.654
And lo and behold, got the same result.

16:28.738 --> 16:31.156
All right.
Can we have two coach seats to Havana?

16:31.240 --> 16:33.075
-The flight is sold out.
-Of course it is.

16:33.159 --> 16:34.242
I'll call the office.

16:35.078 --> 16:36.912
Unless the office can build two seats

16:36.996 --> 16:38.497
and install them on the plane
in the next four hours,

16:38.581 --> 16:40.082
it's not gonna do any good.

16:44.712 --> 16:46.546
Excuse me. Do you speak English?

16:46.631 --> 16:49.174
-Agence France.
-You speak French. Great.

16:49.258 --> 16:51.343
-I speak English, too.
-Okay.

16:51.427 --> 16:55.138
'Cause when I said... It doesn't matter.

16:55.223 --> 16:58.183
I would like to buy your ticket from you
at a substantial markup.

16:58.267 --> 17:00.560
-How substantial?
-Twice what your office paid for it.

17:00.645 --> 17:02.688
You can catch the next
flight and pocket the difference.

17:02.772 --> 17:04.690
-That's a good deal.
-Yes, it is.

17:04.774 --> 17:06.483
I don't have a ticket for the flight.

17:06.567 --> 17:08.318
-You don't?
-No.

17:08.403 --> 17:09.653
What are you doing here?

17:09.737 --> 17:12.698
I'm here to photograph Mr. Snowden.

17:12.782 --> 17:15.450
This is a very big story. You agree?

17:15.535 --> 17:17.119
I do.

17:17.203 --> 17:18.704
I do agree.

17:25.461 --> 17:27.462
We have to get on this flight.

17:30.633 --> 17:33.719
When did you decide
you wanted to be a TV news anchor?

17:33.803 --> 17:35.971
Do you know how long
this interview is gonna take?

17:36.055 --> 17:39.349
-You've got someplace else you're going?
-No.

17:39.434 --> 17:41.685
When did you decide you
wanted to be a TV news anchor?

17:41.769 --> 17:44.396
I didn't. I was a prosecutor.
Then I was a speechwriter.

17:44.480 --> 17:47.232
Then I was the legal correspondent
for my network and I got promoted.

17:47.316 --> 17:50.110
-You were a prosecutor?
-The Brooklyn DA's office.

17:50.194 --> 17:52.904
You aren't afraid you're gonna run
into some of the people you sent here?

17:52.989 --> 17:54.781
That's why I'm supposed to be in solitary.

17:54.866 --> 17:56.658
And you were what kind of writer?

17:57.285 --> 17:58.744
Speechwriter.

17:58.828 --> 18:00.245
What does that mean?

18:00.580 --> 18:03.749
I helped write speeches
for the first President Bush.

18:03.833 --> 18:06.752
I worked on his campaign and when he won,
they brought me to the White House.

18:06.836 --> 18:09.921
No kidding? George H.W.?

18:10.006 --> 18:12.424
-Yeah.
-Did you ever meet him?

18:12.508 --> 18:13.508
Yeah.

18:14.510 --> 18:16.178
Ah. I liked him.

18:16.262 --> 18:18.847
He was an elite
Harvard silver spoon and all that,

18:18.931 --> 18:20.432
but he didn't rub it in your face, you know?

18:20.516 --> 18:22.976
-He went to Yale.
-He didn't do that.

18:23.686 --> 18:25.395
He didn't make people feel stupid.

18:25.480 --> 18:27.606
-That's not what I was doing.
-What?

18:27.690 --> 18:30.275
You were just saying that to the fatheads,

18:30.359 --> 18:32.652
there's no difference
between Yale and Harvard.

18:32.737 --> 18:35.113
But to the refined palate
of the eastern elite,

18:35.198 --> 18:36.740
-the subtle nuances...
-Jesus, I'm from Nebraska!

18:36.824 --> 18:38.700
You still got that
northeastern air of superiority.

18:38.785 --> 18:39.785
I'm in jail!

18:39.869 --> 18:41.620
And even in here
you still think you're better than me.

18:41.704 --> 18:45.290
You hit a woman, man.
You don't set the bar very high.

18:45.374 --> 18:47.751
- Will.
- Yeah?

18:47.835 --> 18:50.378
-You've got visitors.
-On a Monday?

18:57.220 --> 18:59.638
-I'll be outside the door.
-You look good.

18:59.722 --> 19:01.306
Yeah, you say that every week.

19:01.390 --> 19:03.058
It's true every week.

19:03.142 --> 19:04.351
How you holding up?

19:04.435 --> 19:06.645
I'm good. What's this about?

19:06.729 --> 19:09.773
He's going to ask you a couple of
questions I've already approved.

19:09.857 --> 19:12.317
But if you need a minute, take a minute.

19:12.401 --> 19:14.736
-He'll step outside.
-What's going on?

19:14.821 --> 19:16.404
The day before yesterday, Saturday morning,

19:16.489 --> 19:18.949
a woman named Lilly Hart committed suicide

19:19.033 --> 19:22.077
by shooting herself in the head
on the steps of the Justice Department.

19:22.161 --> 19:23.870
Does the name Lilly Hart
mean anything to you?

19:23.955 --> 19:25.121
That wasn't one
of the questions we went over.

19:25.206 --> 19:27.415
-All right.
-Stick to the script.

19:27.792 --> 19:29.960
Lilly Hart worked for BCD.

19:30.044 --> 19:32.921
Her roommate and some of her friends
were trying to put the pieces together,

19:33.005 --> 19:34.631
trying to figure out why she killed herself

19:34.715 --> 19:36.675
-and so theatrically.
-Mmm-hmm.

19:36.759 --> 19:39.511
Her roommate starts going through her emails
and then some files,

19:39.595 --> 19:42.013
and she finds some things
which are alarming enough

19:42.098 --> 19:46.101
for her to bring to the attention
of some agents who sweep the entire laptop.

19:47.770 --> 19:49.938
Will you confirm Lilly Hart as your source?

19:51.649 --> 19:52.816
No, sir.

19:54.610 --> 19:56.111
Will you deny that she was your source?

19:56.195 --> 19:57.696
No, sir.

19:57.780 --> 19:59.990
-You're not under oath.
-I understand.

20:00.074 --> 20:01.992
Lilly Hart has no family.

20:02.076 --> 20:04.619
Both her parents died
in a car crash years ago.

20:04.704 --> 20:06.204
She's single with no children.

20:06.289 --> 20:08.999
There's no one to protect anymore.

20:09.876 --> 20:11.710
Confirm the name,

20:11.794 --> 20:13.837
and I'll inform the judge that the government

20:13.921 --> 20:17.173
no longer needs your testimony
and has withdrawn their subpoena

20:17.258 --> 20:20.677
and you'll be having dinner
with your wife in your home tonight.

20:20.761 --> 20:21.845
Yeah, I'm sorry.

20:21.929 --> 20:25.724
I'm not allowed to reveal the name of a source
without their permission.

20:25.808 --> 20:27.809
Well, that option was taken off the table

20:27.894 --> 20:30.687
when your source
put a loaded Beretta 9mm Nano

20:30.771 --> 20:32.272
in her mouth and squeezed the trigger.

20:32.356 --> 20:34.065
Don't do that. Don't try the side door.

20:34.150 --> 20:37.402
Look, confirm that she's the source
and Neal comes home from Venezuela.

20:37.486 --> 20:39.112
We'll buy the ticket. First class.

20:39.196 --> 20:41.072
And you won't pursue criminal prosecution?

20:41.157 --> 20:42.949
We'll give him an ice cream cone.

20:43.826 --> 20:46.494
Will you confirm
that Lilly Hart was your source?

20:48.080 --> 20:49.331
No, sir.

20:50.708 --> 20:51.750
Will you deny it?

20:51.834 --> 20:53.209
No, sir.

20:55.963 --> 20:59.049
Neal would pummel me if I got him
back by giving up the name of the source.

20:59.133 --> 21:01.134
Did you think
I was gonna consider a deal like this?

21:01.218 --> 21:04.930
I wrote down exactly what I thought you'd say
and sealed it in this envelope.

21:24.533 --> 21:25.951
Can I speak to him?

21:26.035 --> 21:27.410
<i>He's back in his cell.</i>

21:29.246 --> 21:30.538
Mac.

21:30.623 --> 21:32.791
When are they gonna be absolutely sure?

21:32.875 --> 21:34.751
What percent of certainty will it take?

21:34.835 --> 21:37.379
-I'm gonna find out.
<i>-What if we switch places?</i>

21:37.713 --> 21:40.632
<i>-I have the exact same information Will has.</i>
-Mac.

21:40.716 --> 21:44.219
What if you convinced them I was
softer and more likely to give up the name?

21:44.303 --> 21:45.345
<i>-Are you?</i>
-No.

21:45.429 --> 21:47.055
--Just a second.

21:47.139 --> 21:49.099
-What if you told them that...
-Listen to me.

21:49.183 --> 21:51.101
'Cause here's your $20 worth.

21:51.185 --> 21:54.020
You don't tell anyone
you know what Will knows.

21:54.105 --> 21:56.398
You want your friends to be
subpoenaed and get sworn in?

21:56.482 --> 21:58.608
No. Come on in.

21:58.693 --> 22:00.694
Keep calling me.
I want to hear from you once an hour.

22:01.570 --> 22:04.489
-What's going on?
-I need a block tonight. Five minutes, 4:30.

22:04.573 --> 22:06.408
-For what?
-I want to interview Bree Dorrit.

22:06.784 --> 22:09.411
Isn't that the temporary ACN Digital editor?

22:09.495 --> 22:10.495
Yeah.

22:10.579 --> 22:12.539
Why do you want to interview
someone who works for us?

22:12.623 --> 22:14.499
I want to discuss an app he has...

22:14.583 --> 22:17.877
We have called
Human Flesh Hunter or something.

22:18.087 --> 22:19.504
I know I've missed some meetings,

22:19.588 --> 22:22.215
but we really don't have an app
called Hunting Human Flesh?

22:22.299 --> 22:24.092
No. Maybe. I don't know.

22:24.593 --> 22:26.344
I don't like to do stories about us.

22:26.429 --> 22:28.430
I know, but this is about everyone.

22:34.228 --> 22:37.605
Lady Gaga has been
relatively silent on Twitter

22:37.732 --> 22:40.692
since her hip surgery last February.

22:40.776 --> 22:45.488
But today she broke her silence
and tweeted in support of...

22:45.573 --> 22:46.740
In defense of...

22:46.824 --> 22:50.618
In support of overturning
the Defense of Marriage Act.

22:50.870 --> 22:53.288
Sloan's going to interview her manager.

22:55.458 --> 22:58.460
You're still able to hear
yourself when you speak, right?

22:58.711 --> 23:01.546
-Yeah.
-I'm glad Lady Gaga wants to engage people...

23:01.630 --> 23:03.256
She has 40 million Twitter followers.

23:03.340 --> 23:06.384
Does her manager bring expertise
to the table on marriage equality?

23:06.469 --> 23:08.720
What kind of expertise
is there on that subject?

23:08.804 --> 23:10.013
Someone who's familiar with state legislature.

23:10.097 --> 23:12.182
-Just block out the time.
-We don't have the time tonight.

23:12.266 --> 23:13.516
We only have him for one night.

23:13.601 --> 23:16.144
Well, I don't want to get
scooped on Gaga's manager.

23:16.228 --> 23:17.937
Hey, you know what, Mac?

23:18.022 --> 23:21.733
How about she brings 40 million
people to a civil rights debate?

23:21.817 --> 23:24.527
I don't think gay couples
who'd just like to move

23:24.612 --> 23:26.946
the fuck on with their lives
are as choosy about that discussion.

23:27.031 --> 23:28.448
It was trending, Charlie. It still is.

23:28.532 --> 23:31.951
Lady Gaga's tweets,
they're trending number one.

23:32.036 --> 23:34.579
So Pruit picked up
the phone and said, "Do this."

23:34.663 --> 23:37.248
That's why you book her manager,
to report on the tweets.

23:37.333 --> 23:38.583
Whatever. Put it in the rundown.

23:38.667 --> 23:40.585
-I don't have room.
-There's always room.

23:40.669 --> 23:42.754
Tell me what you'd like to cut.

23:42.838 --> 23:47.008
The Supreme Court struck down portions
of the Voting Rights Act this morning.

23:47.093 --> 23:51.262
IAF fighter jets attacked the Gaza Strip
after rockets were fired at southern Israel.

23:51.347 --> 23:53.932
Ed Markey won
John Kerry's seat in the Senate.

23:54.016 --> 23:55.600
-Snowden's on his way to Cuba.
-Cut my thing.

23:55.684 --> 23:57.060
I didn't have the time for it anyway.

23:57.144 --> 23:58.603
- What was it?
- Nothing.

23:58.687 --> 24:00.522
-ACNgage?
-Yeah, how'd you know?

24:00.606 --> 24:02.607
-Pruit wants it.
-How did he know?

24:02.691 --> 24:05.860
The guy, Bree,
he's got a relationship with Pruit.

24:05.945 --> 24:10.115
He told him you were putting him
on the air and Pruit liked it.

24:10.199 --> 24:11.449
It's a promo for the site.

24:11.534 --> 24:14.119
Yeah, that is what it is.

24:14.203 --> 24:16.454
You'll have to cut something else
or make trims.

24:16.539 --> 24:19.124
In an historic 5-4 decision,

24:19.208 --> 24:22.210
the US Supreme Court did something
that we'll tell you about tomorrow.

24:22.294 --> 24:24.295
-We're clear, right?
-We are.

24:29.468 --> 24:32.595
-I'm really sorry.
-Not your fault.

24:32.680 --> 24:36.141
Tell me about the five-minute interview
we're going to do with ourselves.

24:45.776 --> 24:47.902
You sure you wouldn't rather
do this someplace else?

24:47.987 --> 24:49.946
Those are the Footnotes.

24:50.030 --> 24:53.992
The pitch pipe lives in the room next door
and they practice there sometimes.

24:54.076 --> 24:56.327
You get used to it. It's kind of nice.

24:56.412 --> 24:58.413
I just meant...

24:58.497 --> 25:02.125
If I can avoid it, I'd rather not be alone
with a young woman in her dorm room.

25:02.209 --> 25:05.253
You want witnesses in case
I say you forced yourself on me.

25:05.462 --> 25:07.172
-No, no.
-Don.

25:07.256 --> 25:08.506
-Yeah?
-I was raped.

25:09.216 --> 25:11.759
-I wasn't worried...
-I was raped.

25:11.844 --> 25:13.845
I went to a party at one of the eating clubs.

25:13.929 --> 25:15.263
I drank too much tequila.

25:15.347 --> 25:17.932
There was molly, there was coke,
there were mushrooms,

25:18.017 --> 25:19.851
and I took anything
that was put in front of me.

25:19.935 --> 25:22.770
I wound up in a bathroom
throwing up and then passing out.

25:22.855 --> 25:26.858
And the next thing I knew,
two guys were helping me into a bedroom.

25:26.942 --> 25:28.735
They told me I needed to lie down.

25:28.819 --> 25:31.654
When we got in there,
they took my clothes off

25:31.739 --> 25:34.240
and they took turns raping me.

25:40.331 --> 25:42.123
And the next day you called the police?

25:42.208 --> 25:45.210
City police, campus police,
and the DA's office.

25:45.294 --> 25:47.879
I know who the two guys are
and I know where they live.

25:47.963 --> 25:50.715
That should be the easiest arrest
they're ever gonna make.

25:50.799 --> 25:53.051
-Nobody pursued it.
-The kind of rape you're talking about

25:53.135 --> 25:55.762
-is difficult and usually impossible to prove.
-It's not a kind of rape.

25:55.846 --> 25:56.846
Sure.

26:02.686 --> 26:04.896
How did you find me?

26:04.980 --> 26:07.315
-The original email?
-Yeah.

26:07.983 --> 26:09.400
Just some detective work.

26:09.485 --> 26:11.402
I really want to know.

26:11.487 --> 26:14.239
Well, on the web page there's a bio.

26:14.323 --> 26:16.366
You say you're a third-year psych major.

26:16.450 --> 26:19.285
And later you say you live
across from Dillon Gym

26:19.370 --> 26:21.829
and one of these days
you're gonna start working out.

26:21.914 --> 26:24.666
-You also wrote that you love the Phat Lady.
-Right.

26:24.750 --> 26:26.918
I got a list of
all female psych majors on campus

26:27.002 --> 26:29.337
and cross-referenced it with
students living in the upperclassmen dorms

26:29.421 --> 26:31.589
across from the gym,
which brought me to Cuyler Hall.

26:31.674 --> 26:32.632
<i>Wow...</i>

26:32.716 --> 26:35.385
I asked some people in my office
if they knew the band the Phat Lady.

26:35.469 --> 26:38.596
-Really?
-And a Princeton grad laughed and said...

26:38.681 --> 26:39.847
It's a sandwich.

26:39.932 --> 26:43.351
It is the most popular sandwich
not on the menu at Hoagie Haven.

26:43.435 --> 26:46.437
So we went to Costa,
one of the managers at Hoagie Haven,

26:46.522 --> 26:48.982
with pictures of the four female
psych majors living at Cuyler Hall

26:49.066 --> 26:51.442
and asked him if any were regular customers.

26:51.527 --> 26:54.070
He pointed at your picture and
said, "That's my girl, Mary."

26:54.154 --> 26:56.990
That's a lot of detective work.
That's old school.

26:57.074 --> 26:59.158
I was trying to impress my boss.

26:59.243 --> 27:01.536
-My boss' boss.
-Did it work?

27:01.620 --> 27:03.955
He wants you in the studio along with Jeff.

27:05.291 --> 27:06.874
At the same time.

27:09.378 --> 27:12.171
Elliot Hirsch would be moderating,
I guess you'd call it.

27:12.256 --> 27:14.299
It's very promotable.

27:14.383 --> 27:16.301
It'd bring a lot of new viewers to my show,

27:16.385 --> 27:19.721
a lot of younger viewers
who drive a lot of Internet traffic.

27:19.805 --> 27:21.472
And I'd score some points at work.

27:21.557 --> 27:23.349
And you're here for a pre-interview.

27:23.434 --> 27:25.226
I'm here to beg you not to do it.

27:38.073 --> 27:40.992
The travel office
transferred me to talent relations,

27:41.076 --> 27:42.869
who transferred me to Tess, who said,

27:42.953 --> 27:46.331
"It's so romantic that you guys
are on a stakeout together

27:46.415 --> 27:48.666
"in the Moscow Airport. You're his destiny."

27:48.751 --> 27:52.462
I said, "Tess, we were supposed to have
tickets waiting to Havana."

27:52.546 --> 27:54.172
She said, "Hang on, let me check."

27:54.256 --> 27:56.716
Then she got back on the phone and said,

27:56.800 --> 27:59.135
"Did you know there's more than
one city named Havana?"

27:59.219 --> 28:00.595
We have tickets to Spain?

28:00.679 --> 28:03.306
There are layovers in Dvinsk,
Rotterdam, and Berlin.

28:03.390 --> 28:05.475
And we change planes in Madrid.
How's it looking here?

28:05.559 --> 28:08.269
There are three people in front of us,
five people in back of us.

28:08.354 --> 28:11.022
As passengers come to claim their seats,
the people in back get dismissed.

28:11.106 --> 28:13.566
It's like that last helicopter out of Saigon.

28:13.650 --> 28:15.026
I know how standby works.

28:15.110 --> 28:17.070
I was answering your question.

28:21.742 --> 28:24.744
It really would have
killed you to apologize to Hallie?

28:24.828 --> 28:26.829
You would have gotten sick and died?

28:26.914 --> 28:28.706
As soon as you said the word romantic...

28:28.791 --> 28:31.042
-I didn't say it, Tess did.
-You recounted it.

28:31.126 --> 28:33.086
I was telling a funny story.

28:33.170 --> 28:35.254
As soon as you said romantic,
I knew we were heading for Hallie.

28:35.339 --> 28:36.714
After all, it's been two hours.

28:36.799 --> 28:39.008
-You would have tragically died from...
-I did apologize.

28:39.510 --> 28:41.302
"I'm sorry I overreacted.

28:41.387 --> 28:44.889
"In fact, I'm so sorry
that I sent this apology in a text."

28:44.973 --> 28:46.599
How should it have been delivered?

28:46.683 --> 28:49.143
-In person, for starters.
-She doesn't want to see me.

28:49.812 --> 28:51.270
You know what you should do?

28:51.355 --> 28:52.522
Tess thinks you're my destiny?

28:52.606 --> 28:53.773
-Call her right now.
-Tess?

28:53.857 --> 28:55.566
Hallie. Call her right now.

28:55.651 --> 28:57.652
You're halfway around the world
on a big story,

28:57.736 --> 28:59.487
but you just wanted to hear her voice.

